The chapter also provides a LAN security checklist (see p.286-287). What would you add/delete from these lists (2.1.1 and 2.2)? (cite your arguments with scholarly and textbook references)
My company goes through a quarterly security audits every year. They are indeed a pain in the butt but I definitely can see the need. Risk outweigh the annoyance. Looking at the check list the book provides I can see several similarities between the books checklist and my employers. But the significant difference is a greater emphasis on employee information security training and education. I found that our LAN Security Checklists at my work are combined with a complete security checklist, not just for LAN security but for my work as a whole. Honestly I like that better, as it says under LAN Security Assessments understanding the scope and frequency of your whole system. I found a great example of a security checklist from the University of Illinois that is quite in-depth. I also found some great checklists from SANS the checklist I found interesting was one about Safety walkthrough checklist. The checklist from the book goes as follows:

Roles and Responsibilities:
Authorized Users/Groups
Authorized parties responsible for installs and configurations.
LAN Infrastructure Security:
Physical Security
Guidelines and Policies On information being sent
Encryption and Cryptography Policies
Client Device Security:
Acceptable user device policy
Standard hardware and software configurations
Guidelines on how and when a device can be used
Guidelines for stolen or lost devices (remote wipe, encryption, device Identification)
LAN Security Assessments:
Understanding the Scope and Frequency of your whole system
Actions to be taken if rogue or misconfigured devices are identified
Other Recommendations:
Consider designating a progress tracker of security standards.
Maintain an inventory of all devices.
The things I would change on this list:

Add:
Malware, Spyware, Antivirus, Backup software, etc… Properly implemented and Managed
One that I found interesting looking at my company's proper management of unauthorized and authorized web sites be constantly audited and monitored.  
IDS, IPS, and Firewalls properly implemented and managed so we can detect and help prevent attacks.
Guidelines for email. I.E. policy for handling phishing or spam email when it comes into employees mail.
Employee confidentiality agreements if you handle any type of personal data
Access Badge/physical key’s policy. (this might be covered under physical security while I think about it.) I.E. if your security badge is stolen or lost. Or if deactivating previous employees badges.
Proper education and training of employees on new risks and policies.
Remove:
Honestly I like the list the book provides I would just add more, and probably do some combining of current bullet points.
